<br>
However,<br>
<br>
There is another demon out there and that is Junk Mail.  You know that anoyying catalog you keep getting and no matter how many times you call the company to have your name removed you just keep getting it. <br>
<br>
Heres a little truth behind that, and how it works.<br>
<br>
Lets say that you are surfing the web you see a nice little item such as a cool sportcoat from Hammack and Schlemmer (or however its spelled, and btw I dont work for them).  You, who up untill this point have never recieved a catalog, call up Hammacker, and order this cool new sport coat.  Boom, your on thier mailing list.  Not only that, they own your information, that being your name your billing address.<br>
<br>
Now that they own your information, they can sell it to other companies.  Such as Travelsmith, Skymall, Sears, Frontgate, and all the other catalog companies out there.  They literally make a small amount of money from selling your name.<br>
<br>
Suprisingly enough one of the biggest companies that sells your information is the states BMV.  Yes, that is probably one of thier biggest money makers.  The company I work for, when they want a catalog drop on a new market purchases information from the BMV.<br>
<br>
The sad thing is that you often find yourself in a loop if you have ordered from more then one company.  For instance you order from company A, and then order from company B and C.  After a while you get tired of getting all those catalogs, then call up company A B and C, and ask them to remove your name from thier mailing list.  They do, however they continue to sell your name to each other and you still keep getting those damn catalogs.  Oh and never give your email address to any of them either, they sell that information as well.<br>
<br>
Best way to avoid this is to always request that your name and all information never be sold distributed, or promoted in any way shape or form, when placing an order.<br>
<br>
I think most people would be surprised at how big a buisness selling your information really is.<br>
<br>
<br>
